voice_to_text: My boss's daughter said, enjoy the company hoodie and gift card, laughing as she fired me and withholding my 100,000 dollar bonus. During the Series B pitch, the lead investor reviewed my termination papers, slid them back to the CEO and said coldly, congratulations, you just lost your company. I got fired in front of the entire company during our quarterly meeting. No warning, no private conversation, just Madison, the CEO's daughter and our new chief culture officer standing there with a cheap company hoodie and a 50 dollar gift card to some juice bar that doesn't even exist in my area. Unfortunately, your Q4 bonus didn't meet the updated KPI rubric, so it won't be awarded, she announced with this fake sympathetic smile. That bonus was $100,000 and I literally wrote the original KPI rubric she was talking about. Here's the thing. I've been at Tech Vibe for six years. I built their entire operational backbone from scratch. All their back end systems, vendor relationships, fulfillment processes, everything that made the company actually function. Madison had only been there six months, hired straight out of her influencer lifestyle with zero qualifications except being the CEO's daughter. She hated me from day one because people actually respected my work. When I caught her billing an 18,000 dollar wellness experience, that was actually her bachelorette party in Palm Springs, HR told me to focus on positive momentum. When I flagged suspicious budget transfers, she started leaving me out of meetings and Removing my name from projects. But here's what nobody knew. Three months earlier, I'd done something smart, really smart. See, when I rebuilt their tech infrastructure, I did it through my own LLC. I buried a licensing clause deep in the vendor contracts as 12.7 b. It stated that if the company terminated me without formal review and documented cause, the perpetual license to all the systems I'd built would immediately revoke. I ran it through my personal attorney. Everything was legal, signed and filed properly. Their own legal team rubber stamped it without reading carefully. After Madison fired me, I didn't argue. I just smiled, took the hoodie and left. HR didn't even have me sign exit paperwork. That's how sloppy they were. They knew something was off, but they did it anyway. One week later, Tech Vibe had their big Series B pitch with Redwood Capital. They were trying to secure $50 million. Madison was there in her designer outfit giving this polished presentation about culture, forward architecture and strategic partnerships. The CEO looked proud. The board looked confident. That's when Daniel Hayes, the lead investor, opened his due diligence folder. He pulled out my termination memo and read it silently. Then he pulled out the second document, my clause 12.7 b notification letter that I'd sent via certified mail. The room went dead quiet. This termination, Daniel said calmly, was it approved by legal? Madison stuttered. Something about culture fit the CEO.

voice_to_text: My boss said, we're not paying for your little two thousand dollar vacation, denying my work travel. A letter from our largest client arrived during the board meeting. The CEO read it. His expression froze. He slid it to our lawyer, whose only question was, where is she? I used to be the invisible employee. You know the type. The one who fixes everything but gets zero credit. While my boss, Marcus, took credit for my work and meetings. I was the one making panicked calls to suppliers at 3 a m. And saving million dollar deals with duct tape and determination. For eight years, I kept our company running. When our Detroit factory almost shut down because of broken equipment, I called in a favor from an old contact in Serbia. When a shipment got lost in China, I fixed it with three phone calls and some creative problem solving. Marcus would tell the board it was his leadership that saved the day. My reward? Being asked to take notes and grab sparkling water for executives. And came the email that changed everything. Our biggest supplier, Kovach Tech from Hungary, sent a message. They made a specialized computer chip that powered 40% of our company's revenue. Without them, we were done. The founder is on. Kovach said they were changing their buyer list. If we wanted to stay on it, someone needed to attend their annual summit in Budapest in person. I asked Marcus for approval. Just $2,000 for The trip. I explained how critical this was, how we'd lose everything without this relationship. He literally laughed at me. We're not paying for your little vacation, Britney. We have real priorities. I didn't argue. I just smiled. That smile women perfect when they're being insulted and dismissed. That night, I did something crazy. I booked the trip myself. Used my own money, my own vacation days, and a credit card I've been saving for emergencies. Here's what Marcus didn't know. Ten years ago, Istvan's daughter came to America for a project. Her translator bailed. She got food poisoning, and everyone panicked. I was the only one who helped her, found her medicine, stayed with her, called her father when she was scared. We stayed in touch over the years. Christmas cards, birthday emails, small kindnesses that seemed meaningless until they weren't. At the summit, Istvan pulled me aside. Your company sent no one again. His voice was quiet but sharp. I sent four emails, two calls. Silence. Then he said something that stopped my heart. I don't trust them anymore. But I trust you. Will. You represent us in America? Not your company. You personally. I was terrified. I wasn't a business owner. I was just a logistics manager who got ignored in meetings. But that night, I registered my own company. Sharp Point Logistics, LLC. The next day, Istvan and I shook hands on a deal that made me the exclusive distributor of their chips in America. When I got home. I didn't tell anyone. I just kept showing up to work like nothing happened. Marcus was preparing for the big quarterly board meeting, bragging about our rock solid supply chain.

voice_to_text: The girl had always hated her body. One day, a boy handed her a love letter. Inside the letter was a drawing of her with a slightly round belly. When she saw it, she felt crushed. From that day on, she never spoke to the boy again. As time went by, the girl grew even heavier. But the boy kept writing her letters. Every time, she took one from her window, so she walked slowly, and whenever they passed each other, she would awkwardly look down. She both looked forward to reading his letters and feared seeing her name mentioned. Until one day, the boy sent her an invitation, asking her to come over for a date. He hesitated for a long time at first, but eventually said yes. That day, she dressed up carefully. The boy also cleaned his house from top to bottom. Though she still felt uneasy, she gathered her courage and went. When she walked into his house, she saw paintings covering the walls. She noticed that every painting had a corner torn off. Those were the corners from the letters she'd received. She froze, because every beautiful girl in those paintings was actually her. When she turned to look in the mirror, she finally realized she had been seeing herself wrong all along. She was never as ugly as she thought.

voice_to_text: I lifted my leg, showing the rescue words I'd written there. Then I stopped a boy about to get off the bus, trying to signal him for help. But Jack, a near sighted college kid, didn't notice until he put on his glasses. By then, my husband, John, had already woken from his days. Luckily, John didn't suspect a thing. Still, seeing the rage in his eyes, Jack knew he couldn't intervene and hurried off. Facing this rare chance, I took off my scarf and quickly wrote another plea with lipstick. While John wasn't watching, I tossed the scarf toward the driver. I thought he'd spot the words right away, but to my shock, he picked it up angrily and marched over, scolding me for littering. Just as John reached to snatch it back, I panicked, grabbed the scarf myself and quickly apologized, claiming maybe the wind had blown it there. Even so, John's face darkened. He could only hold back his anger in public, waiting until we got home to lash out. Just when I thought all hope was gone, Jack suddenly returned. He asked the driver to wait, said a classmate was still on the way. The driver refused at first, but after Jack offered to pay a waiting fee, he reluctantly agreed. As Jack walked by me again, he suddenly showed me his palm. There were words written on it. Only then did I realize Jack had come back to save me. But as night fell, the Classmates still hadn't arrived. The other passengers grew restless and the driver decided he couldn't wait anymore. When Jack stepped forward to plead again, he suddenly had an asthma attack and collapsed. Panicked, the driver grabbed a first aid kit and shouted for a doctor. John, being a surgeon, rushed over, but froze when he recognized Jack as the same man who had stared at me that morning. Then John saw the faint SOS on my leg. His face twisted with fury. He turned to be Raid Jack, but before he could speak, I grabbed a fire extinguisher and struck him from behind. The blow didn't knock him out. It only enraged him further. Just as John lunged toward us again, the sound of sirens filled the air. The police burst in and in seconds, John was restrained.

voice_to_text: Humans removed their brains and placed them in jars of water. Soon everyone drifted into a deep sleep. At midnight, a zombie carrying a bulging sack crept inside. His job was to steal human brains. But that night his bag was already stuffed full. So he squeezed the last brain into his pocket and hurried off. This mission came straight from God. Each night, zombies had to deliver the brains to heaven, feed them into divine machines for restoration. And only then was the task complete. After a long and weary night, the zombie finally stumbled home. But when he opened his door, he froze. One brain was still in his pocket. Panic hit him. He thought he'd failed. After a long pause, he lifted the brain and pushed it into his own skull. Then, a miracle. The black and white world burst into colour. But with colour came horror. He saw filthy crowds, people relieving themselves in alleys, criminals running wild. Terrified, he yanked the brain back out. Yet the humans before him didn't die. They still slept soundly. After several failed tries, he broke down. He flung the brain away and bolted home in a frenzy. Everything now looked dangerous. Even a rat seemed like a snarling beast. He jumped out the window, landing in a trash bin, and ran as a butcher's shadow chased him down the street. Only then did the truth hit him. This so called mission of collecting human brains was part of a Vast deception. God never wanted to fix the brains. He wanted humans to see the ugly truths they tried so hard to hide.

voice_to_text: In the future, once you turn 18, you're locked inside a sealed room. The only way to survive is to perform in front of a camera and earn tips from whoever is watching. One day, I did a simple backflip and earned 16 credits. I quickly typed a command to buy food, but the money was only enough for a pack of dog food. So I decided to act like a dog, crawling on all fours and eating every bite. Surprisingly, the viewers loved it, and my balance jumped to 30 credits. I used it to buy a shirt and went back to performing. Soon, I had saved 40 credits, enough to buy a bed. At last, for the first time, I felt what success tasted like. I pushed myself to perform even harder. But no matter how much effort I put in, the daily tips I earned were barely enough to feed myself. One night, drunk and furious, I grabbed a bottle and smashed it against the camera. My tips dropped sharply, and in the next second, the power cut off completely. The room went pitch black. That was the system's punishment. I begged for it to come back online, promising I'd behave and perform better next time. Eventually, the lights flickered back on. But this time there was something new. A small window appeared in the corner of the screen. Inside, it was an old man. He introduced himself and explained that once a performer's tips reached a Certain level, the system unlocked new features. I had earned enough to connect with another performer. We could share the screen and make even more money. The old man said he knew a few magic tricks, and if I helped him perform, we could draw a bigger audience. So we began planning. His tricks were clumsy and the mistakes were obvious, but somehow that made it even funnier. People couldn't stop watching. As my skills improved, our shows became more popular. My balance finally passed 2,000 credits. And the system unlocked another feature. Now I could enter other people's rooms freely. Scrolling through random streams, I clicked on a Yoga Girls channel. That's when I noticed something terribly wrong.

C'était l'anniversaire de son petit ami Jordan, Anna avait préparé 1 gâteau en cire d'abeille dès le matin, mais en entrant dans la chambre, elle vit son petit ami avec 1 autre femme. Anna leur brisa le gâteau et fit 1 grimace de colère. Le drame fut diffusé en direct sur le téléphone de sa meilleure amie. Des 1.000.000 de personnes virent en même temps la folie de la présentatrice, commençaient à se moquer d'elle. Le préjudice porté à son image finant seulement perdre beaucoup de fans à Anna, mais elle fut aussi avertie par les annonceurs, si elle ne retrouvait pas sa popularité en 10 jours, elle devrait annuler toutes ses collaborations commerciales, ce qui signifiaient qu'Anna retournerait dans les quartiers défavorisés. Anna était tellement contrariée, elle allait en parler à sa meilleure amie. Elle ne se rendait pas compte des jalousies cachées dans le cœur de Lisa. Lisa se contenta de se persuader qu'elle y arriverait. Le discours confiant d'Anna était trop pour que Lisa puisse faire semblant. Alors elle fit à Paris, elle trouverait 1 garçon sur le campus et en 10 Jours le rendrait aussi populaire que Jordan. Anna accepta volontiers car elle voyait cela comme 1 jeu amusant entre amis. Les filles se rendira alors dans la cour de récréation pour choisir 1 objectif. Bientôt, elle remarquait 1 garçon nommé Cameron. Non seulement il s'habillait de façon démodée, mais il était également extrêmement réservé. Tous se moquait de lui sauf 1 amie d'enfance. En voyant le visage arrogant de Jordan, Anna décida de réformer Cameron. Est parti avant qu'Anna ne puisse finir sa phrase. Le manque d'intérêt de son frère. Elle ne se contente pas de lui parler des hobbies et centres d'intérêt de Cameron, mais lui révéla même des détails de sa vie personnelle. Armée de ses informations, Anna fut avantageée pour séduire le garçon. Elle alla d'abord à l'écurie où il travaillait à temps partiel et fit semblant de le rencontrer par hasard. Ensuite, elle aborda Cameron sur le campus pour lui avouer ce qu'elle ressentait pour lui.

Le lendemain matin, Anne apparu déguisé en princesse, désireuse de profiter de chaque recoin de cette merveilleuse maison. Elle caressait les broderies des murs, observait les vases posés sur la cheminée. Maria continuait à la regarder avec méfiance. Avant de partir, Anne étraignit Mathieu avec force et pris les reines de la charrette pour la conduire aux responsables. En chemin, elle se mire à discuter de manière étonnamment agréable. Soudain, 1 chien surgit sur leur route. Effrayé, le cheval fit 1 écart et la fillette fut projetée. Elle se releva aussitôt, chassa le chien et Calma le cheval. Marie a reconnu en silence la sérénité d'Anne à l'heure arrivée. Elle expliqua aux responsables la confusion. 1 autre famille avait également besoin de main pour travailler. Mais au milieu de ce désordre, Marianne eu pas le cœur de laisser l'enfant. Elle décida de la ramener à gringable pour y réfléchir. Quand Mathieu la vit revenir, il lui adressa 1 sourire complice. Maria annonce à Canne aurait 5 jours d'essai, si elle se comportait bien, elle pourrait rester. Mais dès le lendemain, il découvrir canne avait disparu.
